By taking a look at the data it becomes clear that we are dealing with parliamentarian votes from the lower chamber of the Swiss Parliament, the âNationalratâ or National Council, in the period from the spring session of 2001 to the winter session of 2002. Because we aim to estimate a model based on Bayesian statistical assumptions, we need to choose which two MPs to fix at -1 and +1 on a latent ideological dimension. In Switzerland, as in most liberal democratic polities around the world, we assume these MPs to be on opposing and correct sides of the traditional left-right political spectrum across bills. The traditional left-right dimension has its origins in the very foundation of liberal, multi party parliaments. Using our knowledge of politics and experience of the Swiss political system, weâd like to fix MPs we assume to (almost) never share the same ideal point on said latent dimension. This knowledge, e.g.Â choice of fixed legislators, carries a set of assumptions into the statistical model of the Swiss National Council ideological composition. In Switzerlands case, one can reasonably argue that an MP of the GPS (âGrÃ¼ne Partei Schweizâ) distinctly votes towards the left political extreme, while an MP of the SVP (âSchweizerische Volksparteiâ) votes towards the right political extreme and that these party members are very unlikely to have identical ideal point posterior distributions. Letâs take the MPâs origin into account and select a GPS MP from an city-canton such as Basel Stadt or Geneva, because urban city societies tend to be left leaning in general. We might choose Patrice Mugny, GE (GPS) as our fixed MP at -1. On the other side, we might choose Christoph MÃ¶rgeli, ZH (SVP) as our fixed MP at +1, who is known to have politicized in a populist far-right political frame. Although this choice of legislators might implicate differences on more than one dimension, simply their allegiance to their respective parties, in the Swiss National Council, might suffice to identify the traditional left-right plane.

Bill âSchwangerschaftsabbruch. Revision des Strafgesetzbuchsâ, which aims to reform abortion law, is highly likely to mobilize opinions on the gal-tan ideological spectrum. This particular bill seeks to liberalize abortion practice further by determining a period in early pregnancy, where women can perform an abortion by their own decision, and clearly define the threshold for abortions in later stages of pregnancy, thus overall giving women more power in abortion decisions. We expect this bill to gain support from legislators on the gal side of the spectrum, e.g.Â green-alternative-libertarian legislators, who favor individual freedoms over state-supported traditional values expressed on the tan side of the spectrum, e.g.Â traditional-authoritarian-nationalist values. We do not expect this bill to discriminate along the economic left-right divide, in fact, by taking a look at the Swissvotes (n.d.) website, we see that apart from the Swiss Unionâs Association, no other federal economic or trade association cast a vote recommendation for the popular vote on this bill. We want to model the gal side of the gal-tan dimension with positive values, the according \(beta\) for this bill would look something like \([0, 15]\).

On the other side, we expect the bill âSchuldenbremseâ to mobilize opinions predominantly on the economic left-right dimension. This bill proposes a mechanism for imposing household dept lowering measures, which traditionally is a priority for the economic right, whereas the economic left tends to prefer household spending liberty. The vote on this bill supports these assumptions, as the Green and Socialist parliamentary fractions exclusively voted âNoâ or abstained from the vote. The official documentation on this bill (Curia Vista n.d.) explicitly mentions a âleft-rightâ debate in the National Council. We donât expect this bill to discriminate along the tan-gal ideological dimension, our \(beta\) would accordingly look something like \([15, 0]\).

Display your results graphically (without uncertainty). Write your own code and represent each parliamentarian with a dot. Use colors to distinguish the parties.

The subsequent model alternatives didnât provide a substantial improvement in chain convergence over âstan_fit2â, which leads us to continue our analysis with the first model.

df_thetas <- rstan::extract(stan_fit2)$theta |>
  as_tibble() |> 
  rename_with(~ paste0("theta", .))             
theta_means <- df_thetas |>
  summarise(across(everything(), mean, na.rm = TRUE))
theta_plot_data <- theta_means |>
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(), names_to = "parameter", values_to = "mean") |>
  separate(parameter, into = c("base", "dimension"), sep = "\\.", convert = TRUE) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = dimension, values_from = mean, names_prefix = "dim_") |>
  rename(x = dim_1, y = dim_2) |>
  mutate(mp_id1 = row_number())

theta_plot_data <- theta_plot_data |>
  left_join(mp_info %>% select(mp_id1, labels_main_parties), by = "mp_id1")
party_colors <- c(
  "GPS" = "green",        # GrÃ¼ne Partei der Schweiz
  "SP" = "red",         # Sozialdemokratische Partei
  "CVP" = "orange",        # Christlichdemokratische Volkspartei
  "FDP-Liberale" = "blue", # FDP.Die Liberalen
  "SVP" = "darkgreen",        # Schweizerische Volkspartei
  "Other" = "grey"       # Andere Parteien
)

One cannot but notice a serious flaw in this graphic: The second dimension, which is supposed to represent the tan-gal ideological spectrum, obviously makes little sense, as the âGreen Party Switzerlandâ is on the traditional-authoritarian side together with the SVP, whereas the CVP, a traditionally catholic-conservative party, finds itself on the gal side of the spectrum. This opens questions about identifying assumptions as well as the underlying latent dimension, as the tan-gal dimension is not just inverted. We could have expected difficulties in identifying the second dimension, as the traceplots in FigureÂ 1 pointed to a bad convergence in the second dimension posterior distribution chains.

The most average legislator, e.g.Â the legislator with an estimated ideal point posterior average closest to \(theta[0,0]\) is Walter DonzÃ©, EVP BE. To solidify this claim one needs to take into account confidence intervals from the posterior distribution and observe significant differences to the closest âcontendersâ for the place of most average legislator across dimensions.

legislator_ids <- 1:206

for (i in legislator_ids) {
  df_thetas <- df_thetas %>%
    mutate(!!paste0("distance_legislator", i) := sqrt(
      .[[paste0("theta", i, ".1")]]^2 + .[[paste0("theta", i, ".2")]]^2
    ))
}
distance_cols <- df_thetas %>%
  select(starts_with("distance_legislator"))

results <- distance_cols %>%
  summarise(across(everything(), 
                   list(mean = ~ mean(.),
                        lower_ci = ~ quantile(., probs = 0.025),
                        upper_ci = ~ quantile(., probs = 0.975)))) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(),
               names_to = c("legislator", ".value"),
               names_pattern = "distance_legislator(\\d+)_(.*)") %>%
  mutate(legislator = as.numeric(legislator))

top_10_results <- results %>%
  arrange(mean) %>%
  slice(1:10)

top_10_results <- top_10_results %>%
  left_join(mp_info %>% mutate(legislator = row_number()), 
            by = "legislator")
ggplot(top_10_results, aes(x = reorder(name_for_plotting, mean), y = mean)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "blue") +  # Plot mean values
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lower_ci, ymax = upper_ci), width = 0.2, color = "red") +  # Plot error bars
  labs(
    x = "Legislator",
    y = "Mean Euclidian Distance to 0",
    title = "Top 10 Legislators with Lowest Mean Distance to 0",
    caption = "Error bars show 95% credible intervals"
  ) +
  theme_get() +
  coord_flip()
smallest_counts <- distance_cols %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(smallest_legislator = which.min(c_across(everything()))) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  count(smallest_legislator, name = "count") %>%
  mutate(probability = count / nrow(distance_cols))

# Step 3: Add legislator names
smallest_counts <- smallest_counts %>%
  left_join(mp_info %>% mutate(legislator = row_number()), 
            by = c("smallest_legislator" = "legislator")) %>%
  arrange(desc(probability))

Question 2c

Given that your model is based on very specific data, you may well find other basic dimensions. Describe the two dimensions you see in your visualization.

As we can see in FigureÂ 2, there are some issues with the identification of the second dimension, visualized along the y-axis. When discussing the second dimension, one must remember the potential low convergence in the second dimension posterior distribution chains, as visible in FigureÂ 1. Any discussion on identification of said dimension is consequently followed by an assumption of low quality data (too little information, e.g.Â too many unanimous votes, reiterations of similar votes after deliberation and compromise), and difficulties defining identifiyng assumptions. The wording of specific bills might play a role, as voting âyesâ on a specific bill might correspond to voting ânoâ on another bill, when both bills fundamentally adress the same latent dimension. That said, it is difficult to imagine a credible latent dimension where legislators of the Green Party of Switzerland are closer to members of the SVP than to members of the FDP or even SPS. We can rule out a possible common stance on isolationism (left protects domestic workers, right protects domestic âkinâ) for we have seen in my âHomework 2â results that the GPS and SVP are on opposite sides on the globalist-isolationist spectrum. Even though the data in âHomework 2â stems from the 47th legislative period and the data in this file is from the 46th legislative period, drastic ideological changes between two successive parliaments are unlikely. Concerning the second dimension, we might get clarity by visualizing party averages along the second dimension with confidence intervals.

party_summary <- theta_plot_data %>%

Finally we might get some insight on the second latent dimension traits. We observe some vote convergence between members of the GPS and SVP in these most discriminating bills. Four out of these six bills deal with issues on the Swiss Army, mainly questions of investment in the army for enlarging its operational budget, modernization and foreign deployment mandates. While the GPS tends to oppose such laws, the SVP fraction is often split in its decision, the SP also having a mixed stance oftentimes. The underlying latent dimension which catches these votes splits might seem difficult to identify, as we can imagine the GPS having different reasons for opposing defense budget enlargements as opposed to the SVP. However, a perspective that might just put the GPS and parts of the SVP in the same ideological corner might be the idea on the use of the Swiss Army. Measuring the benefit vs.Â cost ratio of the military apparatus solely on domestic parameters might be a common trait the GPS and SVP share; while the GPS mainly dismisses the military on grounds of non-conformity with Swissâ societiesâ social progression, the SVP argues for a strict orientation on armed neutrality and self-defense. The other side of such a dimension might be an outward orientation on military standards, highlighting military cooperation and modernization in view of foreign powers. One might argue that this is a similar dimension, e.g.Â isolationist-globalist, as in my Homework 2 assignment, but rather than it being defined mainly through economic issues, it describes defense cooperation. One could thus name the second latent dimension in this model pacifistic/non-interventionist - globalist/interventionist. In conclusion though, one must highlight the low convergence in the second dimension. While this label might suit for some of the most discriminating bills, it is obvious that there are plenty of high discriminating bills on the Swiss household for example, where GPS and SVP voted on opposed sides.
